def to_millions(df: pd.DataFrame) -> pd.DataFrame:
    # copy
    df = df.copy()

    # get cols that are not the zone
    cols_not_zone = [col for col in df.columns if col != 'ZONA']

    # each row to millions
    df[cols_not_zone] = df[cols_not_zone].apply(lambda x: x/1e6)
    return df

Take Aways

  • The model is a IMA(1, 1)12 which means that $y_t$ depends on the last error and the last seasonal error.
    • Which can be thought as a simple ARI($\infty$, $\infty$)12 model, which means that $y_t$ depends exponential inverse on the last $y_t$ and the last seasonal $y_t$.
    • In this case it depends $(-0.39)^{n}$ at lag $n$ and $(0.44)^{12n}$ at lag $12n$.
    • Which means that last year sales is positively correlated with the next year sales, but the last month sales is negatively correlated with the next month sales.
  • There is a seaonal pattern of 12 months.
    • In combination with the EDA, we see higher sales in the second semester but decreasing on December.

Particular TS¶

By time we will suppose (and the EDA and last model supports this) that the time series is an additive model. So we can use prophet to forecast the next year.

In [99]:
from prophet import Prophet
from tqdm import tqdm

def prophet_forecast(data, periods=12):
    forecast_df = pd.DataFrame()
    
    for group in tqdm(data.index):
        # Prepare data for Prophet
        df = pd.DataFrame({'ds': data.columns, 'y': data.loc[group].values})
        
        # Fit Prophet model
        model = Prophet()
        model.fit(df)
        
        # Make future dataframe for forecasting
        future = model.make_future_dataframe(periods=periods, freq='M')
        
        # Forecast
        forecast = model.predict(future)
        
        # Store forecasted values in the result DataFrame
        forecast_df[group] = forecast['yhat'].tail(periods).values
    
    # to datetime from 2022-12 to 2023-11
    forecast_df.index = pd.date_range(start='2022-12', periods=periods, freq='M')
    # only get year and month
    forecast_df.index = forecast_df.index.strftime('%Y-%m')

    # flip
    forecast_df = forecast_df.T
    # add index name
    forecast_df.index.name = 'ZONA'
    
    return forecast_df

# Perform the forecast
df_forecast = prophet_forecast(df_sales)

# plot time series of sales
def plot_time_series(df, maxy):
    # copy
    df = df.copy()
    # plot time series using seaborn, lines should be solid
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 5))
    sns.lineplot(data=df.T, dashes=False)
    # set title
    zones = df.index.unique()
    zones = [str(zone) for zone in zones]
    ax.set_title('Time Series of Sales. \nZones: ' + ', '.join(zones))
    # show legend
    ax.legend()
    # x ticks should be dates and only show the semester
    ax.set_xticks(df.columns)
    ax.set_xticklabels(df.columns, rotation=45)
    # set x label
    ax.set_xlabel('Date')
    # set y limits
    ax.set_ylim(0, maxy)

    # show plot
    plt.show()
    return None

# 5 by 5, plot time series of sales
zones = df_forecast.index.unique()
zones = np.sort(zones)
for i in range(0, len(zones), 5):
    plot_time_series(
        df=df_forecast[df_forecast.index.isin(zones[i:i+5])],
        maxy = df_forecast.iloc[:, 1:].max().max()
        )

Take Aways

  • The prophet model forecasted is sound with respect the general sales (only 1 of 12 months is off, which is 8% and is likely to happen at 95% confidence intervals)
  • Projecting sales suggests that zones 28, 12 and 24 will have the highest sales. Can run marketing campaigns in these zones.
  • The worst sales are expected to be zones 22 and 5. Must be careful with these zones.

Segmentation¶

Zones by sales¶

Segment the zones that are correlated with the sales of the company. We will use correlation and clustering to find the zones that are similar in sales.

# use cosine similarity to cluster the zones
from sklearn.cluster import AgglomerativeClustering
from sklearn.metrics import pairwise_distances
from scipy.spatial.distance import cosine

# Cosine similarity function using spearman correlation
def correlation_similarity(data):
    return 1 - pd.DataFrame(data).T.corr(method='spearman').values

# Hierarchical clustering with Ward linkage
def hierarchical_clustering(data, n_clusters):
    D = correlation_similarity(data)
    clustering = AgglomerativeClustering(
        n_clusters=n_clusters, linkage='average', affinity='precomputed', compute_full_tree=True,
        )
    clustering.fit(D)
    return clustering.labels_

# Function to calculate the total within-cluster sum of squares (wcss)
def calculate_wcss(data, labels):
    wcss = 0
    unique_labels = np.unique(labels)
    for label in unique_labels:
        cluster_points = data[labels == label]
        centroid = cluster_points.mean(axis=0)
        wcss += np.sum((cluster_points - centroid) ** 2)
    return wcss

# Elbow method to find optimal number of clusters
def elbow_method(data, max_clusters):
    wcss_values = []
    for i in range(1, max_clusters + 1):
        labels = hierarchical_clustering(data, i)
        wcss = calculate_wcss(data, labels).mean()
        wcss_values.append(wcss)
    return wcss_values

# Generate elbow graph
def plot_elbow_graph(wcss_values):
    plt.plot(range(1, len(wcss_values) + 1), wcss_values, marker='o')
    plt.title('Elbow Method')
    plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
    plt.ylabel('WCSS')
    plt.show()

# Set maximum number of clusters to test
max_clusters = 20

# Perform hierarchical clustering and calculate WCSS for each number of clusters
wcss_values = elbow_method(df_sales, max_clusters)

# Plot the elbow graph
plot_elbow_graph(wcss_values)

# plot time series of sales for each cluster
def plot_time_series_cluster(df, cluster):
    # copy
    df = df.copy()
    # normalize the data by row
    df.iloc[:, :-1] = df.iloc[:, :-1].div(df.iloc[:, :-1].sum(axis=1), axis=0)

    # plot time series using seaborn, lines should be solid
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 5))
    sns.lineplot(data=df[df['cluster'] == cluster].iloc[:, :-1].T, dashes=False)
    # set title
    ax.set_title(f'Relative Time Series of Sales. \nCluster: {cluster}')
    # show legend
    ax.legend()
    # x ticks should be dates and only show the semester
    ax.set_xticks(df.columns[::6])
    ax.set_xticklabels(df.columns[::6], rotation=45)
    # set x label
    ax.set_xlabel('Date')

    # show plot
    plt.show()
    return None

# plot time series of sales for each cluster
for cluster in range(1, n_clusters + 1):
    plot_time_series_cluster(df_clusters, cluster)

Takeaways

Recommendation System¶

Recommend SKUs in zones which respective SKU is not sold. The hypothesis is that the SKU is not sold because it is not available in the zone. The recommendation system will recommend the top 5 SKUs that are not sold in the zone.

Alternating Least Squares¶

We used a BSc project to apply the two-step ALS algorithm to find the best recommendation using matrix factorization. All is implemented only using numpy.

In [479]:
# implement the nDCG metric at P for matrix X and matrix X_hat
def ndcg_at_p(X, X_hat, P):
    # copy
    X = X.copy()
    X_hat = X_hat.copy()
    # get the top P sales for each zone
    top_P = X_hat.apply(lambda x: x.nlargest(P).index.tolist(), axis=1)
    # get the top P sales for each zone
    top_P_true = X.apply(lambda x: x.nlargest(P).index.tolist(), axis=1)
    # get the ideal DCG
    ideal_dcg = top_P_true.apply(lambda x: sum([1 / np.log2(i + 2) for i in range(P)]))
    # get the DCG
    dcg = top_P.apply(lambda x: sum([1 / np.log2(i + 2) if x[i] in top_P_true.iloc[i] else 0 for i in range(P)]))
    # get the nDCG
    ndcg = dcg / ideal_dcg
    return ndcg
